Estimating a model
Models are estimated using model():

pbs_scripts |&gt; 
  model(
    NAIVE(Scripts),
    SNAIVE(Scripts),
    NAIVE(Scripts ~ drift()),
    SNAIVE(Scripts ~ drift()),
  )

# A mable: 1 x 4
  `NAIVE(Scripts)` `SNAIVE(Scripts)` `NAIVE(Scripts ~ drift())`
           &lt;model&gt;           &lt;model&gt;                    &lt;model&gt;
1          &lt;NAIVE&gt;          &lt;SNAIVE&gt;              &lt;RW w/ drift&gt;
# i 1 more variable: `SNAIVE(Scripts ~ drift())` &lt;model&gt;








The mable


A mable (model table) contains 1 row per time series, and 1 column for each specified model.

Visualising forecasts

pbs_scripts |&gt; 
  model(
    NAIVE(Scripts),
    SNAIVE(Scripts),
    NAIVE(Scripts ~ drift()),
    SNAIVE(Scripts ~ drift()),
  ) |&gt; 
  forecast(h = "2 years") |&gt; 
  autoplot(pbs_scripts)

Forecasting with regression
Regression can also incorporate other covariates. For example:

pbs_a10 |&gt;
  model(
    TSLM(Cost ~ trend() + season() + Scripts)
  )

# A mable: 1 x 1
  `TSLM(Cost ~ trend() + season() + Scripts)`
                                      &lt;model&gt;
1                                      &lt;TSLM&gt;








Difficult to forecast


Forecasting with regressors requires you to forecast the regressors too! Useful regressors are easily known, predictable, or controllable.

ARIMA
Unlike earlier models which directly describe trends and seasonality, ARIMA forecasts patterns using autocorrelations (ACFs).






Recall the ACF plot



pbs_scripts |&gt; 
  ACF(Scripts) |&gt; 
  autoplot()

Forecasting accuracy
Evaluating out-of-sample forecasts gives more realistic forecast accuracy results.
For this, we create a training dataset which withholds data for evaluating accuracy.
Then, we produce forecasts from the model that overlap with the withheld ‘test’ data.


fc &lt;- pbs_scripts |&gt; 
  # Keep some data for evaluating forecasts
  filter(Month &lt; yearmonth("2006 Jan")) |&gt; 
  model(
    ETS(Scripts), 
    ARIMA(log(Scripts))
  ) |&gt; 
  forecast(h = "2 years")

Cross-validation accuracy
The stretch_tsibble() function can be added after filter() to create time-series cross-validation folds of data.


fc_cv &lt;- pbs_scripts |&gt; 
  # Keep some data for evaluating forecasts
  filter(Month &lt; yearmonth("2006 Jan")) |&gt; 
  # Cross-validate the remaining data
  stretch_tsibble(.step = 24, .init = 48) |&gt; 
  model(
    ETS(Scripts), 
    ARIMA(log(Scripts))
  ) |&gt; 
  forecast(h = "2 years")

Residual diagnostics
Consider a regression model without seasonality.

fit &lt;- pbs_scripts |&gt; 
  model(TSLM(Scripts ~ trend()))
augment(fit) |&gt; 
  gg_season(.innov)

Residual diagnostics

fit |&gt; 
  select(`ETS(Scripts)`) |&gt; 
  gg_tsresiduals()

Residual diagnostics

fit |&gt; 
  select(`ARIMA(log(Scripts))`) |&gt; 
  gg_tsresiduals()

